# Force a known-good kernel command line regardless of what LK/the vendor
# bootloader injects at handoff. Needed because LK unconditionally passes
# `console=ttyMT0,921600n1 ... printk.disable_uart=1` (the vendor console
# name, not a mainline one) -- see boot.md "First 6.6 Flash" (2026-07-04).
# Without CONFIG_CMDLINE_FORCE, that overrides our own DTS chosen/bootargs
# and mainline never attaches a console to the UART.
#
# CHANGED 2026-07-04: switched from the explicit-address generic form
# (`earlycon=uart8250,mmio32,0x11002000`) to the bare DT-node form. The
# explicit form always selects the generic `early_serial8250_setup` driver
# (8250_early.c), never the MediaTek-specific `early_mtk8250_setup`
# (8250_mtk.c), which is only reachable via OF_EARLYCON_DECLARE matching
# uart0's compatible string ("mediatek,mt6797-uart"/"mediatek,mt6577-uart",
# confirmed in mt6797.dtsi). uart0 is reachable via /aliases serial0 and
# /chosen stdout-path (mt6797-gemini-pda.dts), so bare `earlycon` resolves
# to it and picks up the MTK-specific setup (baud/highspeed-divisor
# handling) instead of assuming plain-16550 register behaviour. Every
# capture so far (cmdline-force, KASLR off, RELOCATABLE off/on) has been
# silent right after el3_exit with the generic form -- see boot.md "Aligned
# kernel_addr retested" and the vendor-baseline entry (2026-07-04) for the
# full diagnostic chain. This is the next untested variable.
# ADDED 2026-07-04 (maxcpus=1): the FIRST successful jump-to-K64 boot
# (logs/2026-07-04-21-scp-node-boot.log) reached Linux 6.6, printed the full
# earlycon log, then HUNG at "smp: Bringing up secondary CPUs ..." on CPU1
# (kernel timestamps stop at [0.016897]; ATF's aee watchdog dumps ~14s later
# and resets the SoC -> reboot loop). Boot single-core to get past the
# SMP/PSCI stall and see how far the kernel proceeds. SMP bring-up is a
# separate problem to fix once we have a stable single-CPU boot (bootability
# first, per CLAUDE.md principle 5).
# ADDED 2026-07-04 (clk_ignore_unused): with maxcpus=1 the kernel booted
# cleanly through all driver init (real ttyS0 console handoff, mtk-wdt took
# over the watchdog) and then went SILENT at exactly
# "clk: Disabling unused clocks" (logs/2026-07-04-23-maxcpus1-boot.log,
# [0.475319]) -- no "Freeing unused kernel memory", no root mount, no panic.
# ~31s later the (un-petted) mtk-wdt fires and resets -> preloader loop.
# Classic incomplete-clock-tree hang: the mainline mt6797 clk driver gates a
# clock the hardware silently depends on because nothing in our DT claims it.
# clk_ignore_unused keeps all clocks on so we can get past this into
# userspace; individual gates can be re-enabled once the clock/DT deps are
# understood.
# ADDED 2026-07-04 (nokaslr): the MSDC0 bring-up hangs silently after probe
# with only an ATF aee_wdt_dump giving a PC/LR pair -- with KASLR's boot-time
# slide active those addresses don't match System.map (looked up as bogus
# omap_dm_timer symbols, a driver not even relevant here). nokaslr keeps
# CONFIG_RANDOMIZE_BASE=y but disables the runtime slide, so a captured PC/LR
# can be symbolicated directly against the vmlinux build. Diagnostic aid only;
# remove once the MSDC hang is root-caused. Left in place now that MSDC is
# deferred (harmless either way) since the msdc0 DT node is disabled.
# ADDED 2026-07-04 (rdinit=/bin/sh): MSDC0/eMMC bring-up is deferred (see
# mt6797-gemini-pda.dts node comment, blockers.md B-7) -- the vendor 2019
# Kali ramdisk's /init script unconditionally does `switch_root` onto
# /dev/mmcblk0p29, which cannot exist without a working eMMC controller, and
# always panics (boot.md "SEVENTH RESULT"). Since eMMC is not required to
# prove kernel bootability (CLAUDE.md principle 5, and the Gemini also has a
# removable SD card as an alternative storage path for later), skip the
# vendor init script entirely and exec a shell directly from the initramfs
# instead, to demonstrate a clean boot to userspace independent of storage.
# REMOVED 2026-07-05 (rdinit=/bin/sh): eMMC now enumerates (mmcblk0, all 33
# partitions -- boot.md FIFTEENTH RESULT, mt2701-mmc compat). Let the vendor
# ramdisk /init run its switch_root onto /dev/mmcblk0p29 to test whether the
# 2019 Kali userspace boots under 6.6 (the remaining half of blockers.md B-7).
# REMOVED 2026-07-06 (clk_ignore_unused): root-caused instead of worked
# around. drivers/tty/serial/8250/8250_mtk.c never enabled the UART's own
# "baud"/infra_uart0 clock (only read its rate), so the late-boot
# clk_disable_unused pass correctly cut power to the only console clock still
# in use, which looked exactly like a hang. Fixed with
# patches/v6.6/serial/0001-serial-8250_mtk-hold-baud-clock-enabled.patch
# (devm_clk_get_enabled() instead of devm_clk_get()), validated on hardware
# build #69 (logs/2026-07-06-69-uart-clk-fix-validation/,
# logs/2026-07-06-70-uart-clk-fix-validation-boot.log) with this flag
# removed -- boot proceeds cleanly to systemd. See boot.md "BUILD
# #62/#65/#67/#69" and blockers.md B-2 item 5 (resolved).
# CHANGED 2026-07-06 (maxcpus=1 -> maxcpus=8): PSCI CPU_ON instrumentation
# (arch/arm64/kernel/psci.c, GEMINI-DEBUG prints) isolated the SMP hang to a
# single cluster boundary. With no maxcpus limit, CPU0-7 (both Cortex-A53
# clusters) bring up cleanly in ~35ms; the hang is specifically at CPU8, the
# first core of the third cluster (2x Cortex-A72). Its PSCI CPU_ON SMC never
# returns -- ATF itself hangs -- consistent with B-13 (upstream mtk-scpsys.c
# MT6797 domain-table bug breaking the shared power domains): the A72
# cluster's power domain almost certainly never gets enabled, so CPU_ON
# blocks waiting on a power rail that never comes up. maxcpus=8 boots all 8
# A53 cores (both little clusters) and avoids the A72 cluster entirely --
# an 8x improvement over maxcpus=1 that doesn't require fixing B-13 first.
# Validated logs/2026-07-06-77-maxcpus8/ + logs/2026-07-06-78-maxcpus8-boot.log:
# "smp: Brought up 1 node, 8 CPUs", clean boot to systemd "running" over
# SSH-over-USB. See boot.md "PSCI CPU1 diagnostic" and "maxcpus=8" entries.
# Full SMP (cpu8/9, A72) blocked on the same fix as Phase 5 display (B-13).
# ADDED 2026-07-06 (initcall_debug, TEMPORARY -- remove with B-13 debug
# patches): build #88 proved the whole synchronous display path completes
# (dsi probe tail clean, one benign CMD_DONE irq, panel registered, master
# bind attempt already deferred before the panel print), yet cpu0 still
# wedges silently ~50ms later with IRQs masked and no marker. initcall_debug
# prints "calling <fn>" / "initcall <fn> returned" for every initcall, so
# the last "calling" line in the capture names the exact function that
# wedges, with no further driver instrumentation needed.
# ignore_loglevel added after build #90: initcall_debug prints at
# KERN_DEBUG, which the default console loglevel (7) suppresses -- build
# #90's capture had the flag on the cmdline but zero "calling" lines.
# rcupdate.rcu_cpu_stall_timeout=6 added after build #92: the wedging
# initcall is cacheinfo_sysfs_init -> cpuhp_setup_state(), which waits on
# every online CPU's hotplug thread in turn -- so the real culprit is an
# unresponsive secondary CPU, not cpu0. A 6s RCU stall timeout makes RCU
# name the stuck CPU and attempt a backtrace before the ~12s ATF watchdog
# resets the SoC (default 21s is too late). TEMPORARY, remove with B-13
# debug patches.
# irqchip.gicv3_pseudo_nmi=1 + CONFIG_ARM64_PSEUDO_NMI TRIED AND REVERTED
# (build #96, 2026-07-06): intended to NMI-backtrace cpu0 after the RCU
# stall report named it as the wedged CPU (see build #94/#95 below). Instead
# it broke boot much earlier: capture showed total silence from el3_exit
# (4.37s) straight to the ATF watchdog (14.38s) -- not even the earlycon
# banner printed, worse than the cacheinfo hang this was meant to diagnose.
# Pseudo-NMI's early ICC_PMR_EL1 priority-mask setup (before console init)
# is evidently mishandled by this device's ATF. Do not re-add without a
# different plan for validating ATF/pseudo-NMI compatibility first. See
# boot.md "BUILD #96/#97".
# ADDED 2026-07-07 (cpuidle.off=1 nohlt, TEMPORARY -- B-13 diagnostic):
# build #129 (boot.md "BUILD #129") proved cpu0 survives the entire B-13
# fatal window when hijacked into an irqs-off poll loop -- the core, arch
# counter, UART and GIC MMIO all keep working, so B-13 is not a hardware
# lock. The distinguishing feature of the poll loop vs normal boot is that
# cpu0 never enters idle/WFI. Prime suspect: cpuidle/WFI entry with the MM
# domain/display clocks registered kills interrupt delivery to cpu0 (the
# vendor 3.18 kernel carries its own MT6797 idle-driver hacks).
# cpuidle.off=1 disables the cpuidle framework; nohlt forces poll-idle
# (never executes WFI). If boot completes with these, B-13 is a
# cpuidle/WFI interaction and we have a workaround.
# REMOVED 2026-07-07 same day (build #131, logs/2026-07-07-132-…): NO
# effect — identical hang at 2.63s with both flags confirmed active. So
# the wedge is triggered by taking an interrupt (irqs-off spin survives,
# irqs-on poll-idle dies), not by WFI/idle. See boot.md "BUILD #131".
# REMOVED 2026-07-07: initcall_debug/ignore_loglevel/rcu_cpu_stall_timeout
# were B-13 cpu0-hang diagnostics (see above); B-13 is root-caused and fixed
# (drm/0008), and the flags were flooding the 4MB dmesg ring buffer fast
# enough to evict early boot output (panel/DSI probe messages) within ~2
# minutes of uptime, hiding the data needed for the next debugging pass.
# ADDED 2026-07-08 (g_ether.dev_addr/host_addr): CONFIG_USB_ETH is built-in
# (=y, not a module), so g_ether has no persistent MAC and randomizes one on
# every boot -- macOS keys its Ethernet "service" identity off the MAC, so a
# random MAC means a brand-new enNN interface (and RNDIS/CDC-ECM network
# service) every single boot, indistinguishable in casual troubleshooting
# from "the gadget never comes up", and it defeats any attempt to pin a
# static IP/service on the Mac side. Built-in drivers still honor
# "<modname>.<param>=" on the kernel cmdline, so fix both ends of the link to
# fixed locally-administered MACs (bit 0x02 set, per IEEE 802) instead of
# random ones.
# REMOVED 2026-07-12 (clk_ignore_unused): TEMPORARY flag from the 2026-07-10
# scanout-crash diagnosis, dropped for the production display build (#145).
# The original note:
# clk_ignore_unused re-added for ONE build to separate the two suspects for
# the WDT reset at first real scanout (capture 242): late clk cleanup vs.
# SMI larb0 IOMMU-bypass gap. If the crash persists with this flag, the
# clk path is exonerated.
# ADDED 2026-07-12 (fbcon=rotate:3 + font:TER16x32): first fbcon on the
# physical panel (build #138, banner #122 — vendor video timings). The
# panel is native portrait 1080x2160 but the device is used landscape
# (clamshell keyboard), so rotate the console 90° counter-clockwise (rotate:3); the default
# 8x16 font is unreadably small at ~400 dpi, so use the large Terminus
# 16x32 (CONFIG_FONT_TER16x32=y in gemini-display.config).
CONFIG_CMDLINE="console=ttyS0,921600n1 earlycon maxcpus=8 nokaslr fbcon=rotate:3 fbcon=font:TER16x32 g_ether.dev_addr=42:00:15:19:82:01 g_ether.host_addr=42:00:15:19:82:00"
CONFIG_CMDLINE_FORCE=y

# REVERTED 2026-07-04: previously disabled CONFIG_RANDOMIZE_BASE/RELOCATABLE
# here, chasing a text_offset=0x0 red herring. That was wrong and actively
# harmful: RELOCATABLE=y (the arch/arm64 default) is the exact mechanism that
# lets a legacy/naive bootloader like this device's LK boot a modern kernel
# at all. LK hardcodes the kernel load address to dram_base+0x80000
# (0x40080000) -- confirmed 2026-07-04 by overriding boot.img's kernel_addr
# field to a 2MB-aligned address and observing LK still print
# "[LK]jump to K64 0x40080000" (the override was silently ignored). 0x40080000
# is NOT 2MB-aligned, so the kernel depends on its own early relocation code
# (gated by CONFIG_RELOCATABLE) to copy itself to a valid boundary before
# continuing. Disabling RELOCATABLE removed that self-relocation and is the
# likely reason every post-el3_exit capture has been silent. Leaving both
# configs at their defconfig defaults (unset here = default y) going forward.
# See boot.md "Aligned kernel_addr retested -- LK ignores header field"
# (2026-07-04).
